Hi S�ren,

I cannot rember exact behavior of the PathScope, I will have to look it 
up. But I think that DecidingScope&#39;s seeds-as-surt-prefixes option will 
do what you need. When this option is true all seeds are converted to 
surt prefixes. This conversion has two rules as follow:

1) Everything after the last / in the path is dropped before conversion. 
Examples are:

Seed http://archive.org/ is converted into http://(org,archive,)/ surt 
prefix.

Seed http://archive.org/web/web.php is converted into 
http://(org,archive,)/web/ surt prefix.

Seed http://archive.org/bla is converted into http://(org,archive,)/

I believe that this is similar to PathScope if not exactly the same.

2) If a &quot;slash page&quot; does not have trailing slash it is converted into 
the &quot;domain&quot; scope prefix. Example:

Seed http://archive.org is converted to http://(org,archive,


If you trust your seeds to have a trailing slash so that 2) is avoided, 
setting seeds-as-surt-prefixes to true will behave as PathScope.

In general, I strongly recommend to separate seeds from scope. In other 
words, do not use seeds for scoping. This can be achieved by using scope 
directives either mixed with seeds or in a separate scope source. The 
scope directive entires start with &#39;+&#39; and the rules are as follow:

1) Host scope

+http://archive.org/ is converted into http://(org,archive,)/ surt prefix

+http://(org,archive,)/ is converted into http://(org,archive,)/ surt 
prefix (only plus is removed).

2) Domain scope
+http://archive.org is converted into http://(org,archive, surt prefix

+http://(org,archive, is converted into http://(org,archive, surt prefix 
(only plus is removed)

+dk is converted into http://(dk, surt prefix (entire .dk domain)

+co.yu is converted into http://(yu,co, surt prefix (entire .co.yu domain).

3) Path scope

+http://archive.org/ is converted into http://(org,archive,)/

+http://(org,archive,)/ is converted into http://(org,archive,)/

+http://archive.org/web/web.php is converted into http://(org,archive,)/web/

+http://archive.org/bla is converted into http://(org,archive,)/

+http://(org,archive,)/bla is converted into http://(org,archive,)/bla


I hope this helps.

Take care,
i.


